':205,'multiline':False]['text':' |x| >= |v|, CF2_ik converges rapidly','line_number':215,'multiline':False]['text':' |x| -> 0, CF2_ik fails to converge','line_number':216,'multiline':False]['text':' Steed's algorithm, see Thompson and Barnett,','line_number':220,'multiline':False]['text':' Journal of Computational Physics, vol 64, 490 (1986)','line_number':221,'multiline':False]['text':' b1','line_number':224,'multiline':False]['text':' D1 = 1 / b1','line_number':225,'multiline':False]['text':' f1 = delta1 = D1, coincidence','line_number':226,'multiline':False]['text':' q0','line_number':227,'multiline':False]['text':' q1','line_number':228,'multiline':False]['text':' Q1 = C1 because q1 = 1','line_number':229,'multiline':False]['text':' S1','line_number':230,'multiline':False]['text':' starting from 2','line_number':237,'multiline':False]['text':' continued fraction f = z1 / z0','line_number':239,'multiline':False]['text':' series summation S = 1 + \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} C_n * z_n / z_0','line_number':246,'multiline':False]['text':' forward recurrence for q','line_number':249,'multiline':False]['text':'','line_number':253,'multiline':False]['text':' Under some circumstances q can grow very small and C very','line_number':254,'multiline':False]['text':' large, leading to under/overflow.  This is particularly an','line_number':255,'multiline':False]['text':' issue for types which have many digits precision but a narrow','line_number':256,'multiline':False]['text':' exponent range.  A typical example being a "double double" type.','line_number':257,'multiline':False]['text':' To avoid this situation we can normalise q (and related prev/current)','line_number':258,'multiline':False]['text':' and C.  All other variables remain unchanged in value.  A typical','line_number':259,'multiline':False]['text':' test case occurs when x is close to 2, for example cyl_bessel_k(9.125, 2.125).','line_number':260,'multiline':False]['text':'','line_number':261,'multiline':False]['text':' S converges slower than f','line_number':270,'multiline':False]['text':' Compute I(v, x) and K(v, x) simultaneously by Temme's method, see','line_number':297,'multiline':False]['text':' Temme, Journal of Computational Physics, vol 19, 324 (1975)','line_number':298,'multiline':False]['text':' Kv1 = K_(v+1), fv = I_(v+1) / I_v','line_number':302,'multiline':False]['text':' Ku1 = K_(u+1), fu = I_(u+1) / I_u','line_number':303,'multiline':False]['text':' v is non-negative from here','line_number':322,'multiline':False]['text':' -1/2 <= u < 1/2','line_number':326,'multiline':False]['text':' any value will do','line_number':345,'multiline':False]['text':' reflection formula','line_number':353,'multiline':False]['text':' x is positive until reflection','line_number':361,'multiline':False]['text':' Wronskian','line_number':362,'multiline':False]['text':' x in (0, 2]','line_number':363,'multiline':False]['text':' Temme series','line_number':365,'multiline':False]['text':' x in (2, \infty)','line_number':367,'multiline':False]['text':' continued fraction CF2_ik','line_number':369,'multiline':False]['text':' forward recurrence for K','line_number':377,'multiline':False]['text':' x is huge compared to v, CF1 may be very slow','line_number':403,'multiline':False]['text':' to converge so use asymptotic expansion for large','line_number':404,'multiline':False]['text':' x case instead.  Note that the asymptotic expansion','line_number':405,'multiline':False]['text':' isn't very accurate - so it's deliberately very hard ','line_number':406,'multiline':False]['text':' to get here - probably we're going to overflow:','line_number':407,'multiline':False]['text':' continued fraction CF1_ik','line_number':416,'multiline':False]['text':' Wronskian relation','line_number':417,'multiline':False]['text':' any value will do','line_number':421,'multiline':False]['text':' reflection formula','line_number':432,'multiline':False]['text':' namespaces','line_number':447,'multiline':False]['text':'